{"title_page": "Kim Jong-gwan", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Kim Jong-gwan\n|image        = \n|caption      = \n|office       = [[Ministry of People's Armed Forces|Minister of People's Armed Forces]]\n|order        = \n|term_start   = December 2019\n|term_end     = \n|deputy       = \n|1blankname   = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n|1namedata    = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|predecessor  = [[No Kwang-chol]]\n|successor    = \n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = [[North Korea]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|religion     = \n|nickname     = \n|allegiance   = {{flag|North Korea}}\n|branch       = \n|serviceyears = \n|rank         =  [[File:General of the Army rank insignia (North Korea).svg|25px]] [[Daejang|Army General]]\n|commands     = \n|battles      = \n|education    = \n|mawards      = \n|party        = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n}}\n'''Kim Jong-gwan ({{lang-ko|\uae40\uc815\uad00}})''' is a North Korean politician and military officer who is the [[Minister of People's Armed Forces]] Since December 2019.\n\n==Biography==\nHe is the Lieutenant General of the Korean People's Army, and previously commanded the General Construction Bureau. In May 2016, he was appointed a member of the [[7th Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|7th]] [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] at the [[7th Congress of the Workers' Party of Korea]].<ref>[http://www.nocutnews.co.kr/news/4591096 ]</ref> In March 2009, he [[2009 North Korean parliamentary election|was elected]] the 12th convocation for the 334th district of the [[Supreme People's Assembly]]<ref>[http://repo.kinu.or.kr/bitstream/2015.oak/1365/1/0001391352.pdf \ucd5c\uace0\uc778\ubbfc\ud68c\uc758 \ub300\uc758\uc6d0 \uc120\uac70 \uacb0\uacfc \ubd84\uc11d]</ref>. He was a member of the Funeral committee of [[Ri Ul-sol]] who died in August 2015 and [[Kim Yong-chun]] who died in August 2018.<ref>[http://www.tongilnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=125893 ]</ref> On December 2019 he was appointed to the [[Ministry of People's Armed Forces|Minister of People's Armed Forces]] and promoted to General<ref>[https://news.joins.com/article/23688103 ]</ref> and became also a permanent member of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Politburo]] of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Pak Yong-sik]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of People's Armed Forces|Minister of People's Armed Forces]]|years=December 2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:North Korean generals]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n[[Category:Defence ministers of North Korea]]\n\n{{NorthKorea-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Kim Jong-gwan\n|image        = \n|caption      = \n|office       = [[Ministry of People's Armed Forces|Minister of People's Armed Forces]]\n|order        = \n|term_start   = December 2019\n|term_end     = \n|deputy       = \n|1blankname   = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n|1namedata    = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|predecessor  = [[No Kwang-chol]]\n|successor    = \n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = [[North Korea]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|religion     = \n|nickname     = \n|allegiance   = {{flag|North Korea}}\n|branch       = \n|serviceyears = \n|rank         =  [[File:General of the Army rank insignia (North Korea).svg|25px]] [[Daejang|Army General]]\n|commands     = \n|battles      = \n|education    = \n|mawards      = \n|party        = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n}}\n'''Kim Jong-gwan ({{lang-ko|\uae40\uc815\uad00}})''' is a North Korean politician and military officer who is the [[Minister of People's Armed Forces]] Since December 2019.\n\n==Biography==\nHe is the Lieutenant General of the Korean People's Army, and previously commanded the General Construction Bureau. In May 2016, he was appointed a member of the [[7th Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|7th]] [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] at the [[7th Congress of the Workers' Party of Korea]].<ref>[http://www.nocutnews.co.kr/news/4591096 ]</ref> In March 2009, he [[2009 North Korean parliamentary election|was elected]] the 12th convocation for the 334th district of the [[Supreme People's Assembly]]<ref>[http://repo.kinu.or.kr/bitstream/2015.oak/1365/1/0001391352.pdf \ucd5c\uace0\uc778\ubbfc\ud68c\uc758 \ub300\uc758\uc6d0 \uc120\uac70 \uacb0\uacfc \ubd84\uc11d]</ref>. He was a member of the Funeral committee of [[Ri Ul-sol]] who died in August 2015 and [[Kim Yong-chun]] who died in August 2018.<ref>[http://www.tongilnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=125893 ]</ref> On December 2019 he was appointed to the [[Ministry of People's Armed Forces|Minister of People's Armed Forces]] and promoted to General<ref>[https://news.joins.com/article/23688103 ]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Pak Yong-sik]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of People's Armed Forces|Minister of People's Armed Forces]]|years=December 2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:North Korean generals]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n[[Category:Defence ministers of North Korea]]\n\n{{NorthKorea-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kim_Jong-gwan"}
{"title_page": "National Guard of Niger", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= Garde Nationale du Niger\n|dates= As Republican Guard: 1963\u20131997<br />As Forces Nationales d'Intervention et Securite: 1997\u20132011 <br/ > As National Guard: 2011-Present\n|image=Nigerien soldier in Diffa 2016.jpg\n|caption=A soldier of the National Guard deployed in [[Diffa]] against [[Boko Haram]] in 2016\n|country= {{nowrap|{{flag|Niger}}}}\n|branch=\n|type=\n|role= [[Paramilitary forces (Niger)|Paramilitary forces of Niger]]\n|size= 3,200 end strength (FY2005)\n|command_structure= [[Ministry of Interior (Niger)|Ministry of Interior]]\n|current_commander=  Chef d'Escadron [[Oumarou Taway\u00e9]]<br />[[Superior Commander of the National Guard (Niger)|Superior Commander, National Guard]]\n|garrison=\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|colonel_of_the_regiment=\n|patron=\n|motto=\n|colors=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|battles=\n}}\nFormerly known as the Forces Nationales d\u2019Intervention et de Securit\u00e9 (1997-2011)<ref name=\"hdn\">Historical Dictionary of Niger pp. 244</ref><ref name=\"dcaf\">[http://www.dcaf.ch/Publications/Security-Sector-Governance-in-West-Africa] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714215853/http://www.dcaf.ch/Publications/Security-Sector-Governance-in-West-Africa |date=2014-07-14 }} Gouvernance du secteur de la s\u00e9curit\u00e9 en Afrique de l\u2019Ouest: les d\u00e9fis \u00e0 relever \u2013 Le Niger</ref> and Garde Republicaine (1963-1997),<ref name=\"dcaf\" /> the '''Nigerien National Guard''' ({{lang-fr|Garde Nationale du Niger}}) is a paramilitary corps of the Armed Forces of Niger under the control of the Ministry of Interior. It is headed by the superior commander of the national guard.\n\n== History ==\nThe National Guard was first created in 1963 as the Republican Guard under the presidency of President [[Hamani Diori|Diori Hamani]]. Due to its loyalty to President Hamani, following the [[1974 Nigerien coup d'\u00e9tat|1974 coup]] by President [[Seyni Kountch\u00e9|Seyni Kountche]], it was restructured to ensure loyalty to Seyni Kountche. During those years, the guard was primarily tasked of protecting the president and was made up of elite soldiers trained by Moroccan officers.<ref name=\"hdn\"/> After the 1995 peace agreements between the government of Niger and the Touareg rebel groups, it was restructured and renamed to \"Forces Nationales d'Interventions and Securite (FNIS)\". Ex-rebel members were reinserted into this body as per the terms of the peace agreements. Previously under the authority of [[Ministry of Defense (Niger)|Ministry of Defense]], the national guard was transferred under the authority of the [[Ministry of Interior (Niger)|Ministry of Interior]] in 2003. Faithful to their tradition, the National Guard remained loyal to President [[Mamadou Tandja|Tandja Mamadou]] in his attempt to prolong his presidency beyond the constitutional limits of his term. Later, during the [[2010 Nigerien coup d'\u00e9tat|2010 military coup]], the National Guard unsuccessfully defended President Tandja Mamadou.<ref name=\"hdn\"/> In 2010 and 2011, several government decrees and ordinances proceeded to its reorganization and renaming to the National Guard of Niger.\n\n== Mission ==\nThe mission of the national guard of Niger is defined by ordinance n\u00b0201-61 of October 7, 2010 and consists of:<ref name=\"ngn-niger\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ibcr.org/editor/assets/NIGER%20etat_int_epr3.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-06-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714213622/http://www.ibcr.org/editor/assets/NIGER%20etat_int_epr3.pdf |archivedate=2014-07-14 }} Garde nationale du Niger</ref> \n* monitoring the national territory\n* maintaining public safety and restoring public order\n* protecting public buildings, people and their property\n* participating in defense emergency preparedness\n* carrying out judiciaries and administrative inquiries \n* conducting policing duties in rural areas and pastorals\n* providing honor services for the authorities \n* providing protection to republican institutions\n* participating in the operational territorial defense\n* providing administration, management and monitoring of prisons\n* participating in development activities in the country (i.e. humanitarian operations)\n* participating in peacekeeping in international commitments made by the Niger,\n* protecting the environment\n* searching and detecting offenses under the criminal laws\n* providing assistance to administrative authorities and the diplomatic and consular representations of Niger\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|National Guard of Niger}}\n\n[[Category:Military of Niger]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= Garde Nationale du Niger\n|dates= As Republican Guard: 1963\u20131997<br />As Forces Nationales d'Intervention et Securite: 1997\u20132011 <br/ > As National Guard: 2011-Present\n|image=Nigerien soldier in Diffa 2016.jpg\n|caption=A soldier of the National Guard deployed in [[Diffa]] against [[Boko Haram]] in 2016\n|country= {{nowrap|{{flag|Niger}}}}\n|branch=\n|type=\n|role= [[Paramilitary forces (Niger)|Paramilitary forces of Niger]]\n|size= 3,200 end strength (FY2005)\n|command_structure= [[Ministry of Interior (Niger)|Ministry of Interior]]\n|current_commander=  Chef d'Escadron [[Oumarou Taway\u00e9]]<br />[[Superior Commander of the National Guard (Niger)|Superior Commander, National Guard]]\n|garrison=\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|colonel_of_the_regiment=\n|patron=\n|motto=\n|colors=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|battles=\n}}\nFormerly known as the Forces Nationales d\u2019Intervention et de Securit\u00e9 (1997-2011)<ref name=\"hdn\">Historical Dictionary of Niger pp. 244</ref><ref name=\"dcaf\">[http://www.dcaf.ch/Publications/Security-Sector-Governance-in-West-Africa] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714215853/http://www.dcaf.ch/Publications/Security-Sector-Governance-in-West-Africa |date=2014-07-14 }} Gouvernance du secteur de la s\u00e9curit\u00e9 en Afrique de l\u2019Ouest: les d\u00e9fis \u00e0 relever \u2013 Le Niger</ref> and Garde Republicaine (1963-1997),<ref name=\"dcaf\" /> the '''Nigerien National Guard''' ({{lang-fr|Garde Nationale du Niger}}) is a paramilitary corps of the Armed Forces of Niger under the control of the Ministry of Interior. It is headed by the superior commander of the national guard.\n\n== History ==\nThe National Guard was first created in 1963 as the Republican Guard under the presidency of President Diori Hamani. Due to its loyalty to President Hamani, following the 1974 coup by President Seyni Kountche, it was restructured to ensure loyalty to Seyni Kountche. During those years, the guard was primarily tasked of protecting the president and was made up of elite soldiers trained by Moroccan officers.<ref name=\"hdn\"/> After the 1995 peace agreements between the government of Niger and the Touareg rebel groups, it was restructured and renamed to \"Forces Nationales d'Interventions and Securite (FNIS)\". Ex-rebel members were reinserted into this body as per the terms of the peace agreements. Previously under the authority of [[Ministry of Defense (Niger)|Ministry of Defense]], the national guard was transferred under the authority of the [[Ministry of Interior (Niger)|Ministry of Interior]] in 2003. Faithful to their tradition, the National Guard remained loyal to President Tandja Mamadou in his attempt to prolong his presidency beyond the constitutional limits of his term. Later, during the 2010 military coup, the National Guard unsuccessfully defended President Tandja Mamadou.<ref name=\"hdn\"/> In 2010 and 2011, several government decrees and ordinances proceeded to its reorganization and renaming to the National Guard of Niger.\n\n== Mission ==\nThe mission of the national guard of Niger is defined by ordinance n\u00b0201-61 of October 7, 2010 and consists of:<ref name=\"ngn-niger\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ibcr.org/editor/assets/NIGER%20etat_int_epr3.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-06-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714213622/http://www.ibcr.org/editor/assets/NIGER%20etat_int_epr3.pdf |archivedate=2014-07-14 }} Garde nationale du Niger</ref> \n* monitoring the national territory\n* maintaining public safety and restoring public order\n* protecting public buildings, people and their property\n* participating in defense emergency preparedness\n* carrying out judiciaries and administrative inquiries \n* conducting policing duties in rural areas and pastorals\n* providing honor services for the authorities \n* providing protection to republican institutions\n* participating in the operational territorial defense\n* providing administration, management and monitoring of prisons\n* participating in development activities in the country (i.e. humanitarian operations)\n* participating in peacekeeping in international commitments made by the Niger,\n* protecting the environment\n* searching and detecting offenses under the criminal laws\n* providing assistance to administrative authorities and the diplomatic and consular representations of Niger\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|National Guard of Niger}}\n\n[[Category:Military of Niger]]\n", "name_user": "Le Petit Chat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Guard_of_Niger"}
{"title_page": "Doja Cat discography", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist       = [[Doja Cat]]\n| Image        = Doja Cat Hot Pink Party2.png \n| Caption      = Doja Cat performing at the [[Museum of Sex]] in November 2019\n| Alt          = Refer to caption\n| Studio       = 2\n| EP           = 1\n| Singles      = 17\n| Music videos = 7\n| Option       = 2\n| Option name  = Promotional singles}}\n\nAmerican singer, rapper and songwriter [[Doja Cat]] has released two [[studio album]]s, one [[extended play]] (EP), 17 [[Single (music)|single]]s (including three as a featured artist), 7 [[music video]]s and two [[promotional single]]s.\n\n==Studio albums==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+List of studio albums, with selected details and chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:8em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\" | Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\" | Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref>Peaks on the US ''Billboard'' 200:\n* ''Amala'': {{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/2019-11-09?rank=138|title=Billboard 200: November 9, 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}\n* ''Hot Pink'': {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/2020-03-14|title=Top 200 Albums: March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|US<br>R&B<br>/HH]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/r-b-hip-hop-albums/2020-03-14|title=Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums - March 14, 2020|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard charts#Albums|US<br>R&B]]<br><ref>Peaks on the US R&B Albums Chart:\n* ''Amala'': {{cite 